@endnode


# #
# # 1 Configuration
# # 1.1 Configuration matérielle
# #
@node ConfigMat "Hardware configuration required"

    @{b}"Standard" Version@{ub}

      Hardware configuration: An AMIGA, with a 68020 or superior (sorry for
      others, but I think that currently, 68020 is the vital minimum for an
      AMIGA.) The chipset OCS is sufficient, 1Mo of RAM.

      Concerning the speed of execution... Do not hope miracles, on an
      A1200 of basis, AMI-CPC is approximately 10 times slower than a true
      CPC.  With the FASt memory, one redescend to 6 times slower...
      This is why, I recommend at least 1Mo FAST-RAM and a 68030
      or more...

    @{b}"Turbo" Version@{ub}
      An AMIGA, with a 68020 or superior, the chipset minimum OCS, 2,5Mo
      of FAST RAM are the minimum (ATTENTION:  the memory has to be
      continuous!), 512K of CHIP RAM.

      The "Turbo" version is approximately 20% faster than the "Standard"
      version, it uses a mapping memory that avoids to use a decoding of the
      selection of ROMS/RAMS of the CPC...
      There again, I strongly recommend 4Mo FAST with a 68030 or more...

    @{b}Compatibility@{ub}
      AMI-CPC has been tested successfully on next configurations:
      - A1200 standard (no FAST, 68020 at 14Mhz),
      - A1200 + 4Mo of FAST,
      - A1200, 68030 at 28Mhz, 4Mo of FAST,
      - A1200, 68030 at 50Mhz, 4Mo of FAST,
      - A1200, 68060 at 50Mhz, 16Mo of FAST,
      - A2000 (Kick 2.0), 68030 to 22Mhz.
      I think that it would work well on all machines having the required
      configuration. (There is no direct access to the equipment, all is
      made by using system calls.)

@endnode


##
## 1.2 Configuration logicielle
##
@node ConfigSoft "Software configuration required"

    SoftWare configuration: Kickstart 2.0 or superior. There also, the
    Kick 1.3 is no longer reasonable...

  @{b}ROMS@{ub}
    It has equally needed a copy of 3 ROMS of a CPC 6128. These ROMS are (c)
    Copyright @{b}Amstrad to Consume Electronic plc@{ub} and
    @{b}Locomotive Software Ltd@{ub}. (See @{"Copyright" link Copyrights}).

    Their names have to be following : (or you should uses the @{"tooltypes" link Lancement_WB})

    - LROM, for the inferior ROM (BIOS AMSTRAD)
    - UROM, for the ROM superior (BASIC AMSTRAD) 
    - ROM7, for the floppy ROM (AMSDOS)


    (I have used the same names for @{" CPE " link CopyRights}, an other AMSTRAD emulator
    that I have discovered some times ago, thus, if you possess already @{" CPE " link CopyRights},
    you can reuse its ROMS files directly with AMI-CPC.)
    
    ROMS files have to be found in the same directory that the emulator.

  @{b}Diskette File@{ub}
    Endly, AMI-CPC needs the file DISC.DSK, that contains an image
    of a CPC diskette. This file has to be found in the same
    repertory that the emulator too, or you can use the Workbench and the 
    @{"tooltypes" link Lancement_WB}.

@endnode


##
## 2 Launching
## 2.1 Since the SHELL
##
@node Lancement_SHELL "Launching since the Shell"

    Under a window shell, just type "AMI-CPC" (the name of
    the executable) to run it. A window of invites opens to adjust
    parameters:

    - The selection of the name of the CPC: in fact, it concerns to
      switch the 3 bridges LK1, LK2, LK3 of the mother card of the CPC
      allowing to choose the name of the constructor...

    - The gadget "Avec sons" allows if it is checked to use the sounds in
      the emulation of the CPC.  If this gadget is not selected, AMI-CPC
      will not allocate audios channels, and they will be therefore free
      to others tasks (a module player, for example...)

    - The gadget OK allows to start the emulator, it tries to read ROMS
      of the CPC, to open a public screen, then to open the diskette
      file DISC.DSK.

    - The close-gadget of the window leaves the program.

@endnode


##
## 2.2 Since the Workbench
##
@node Lancement_WB "Launching since the Workbench"

    From the Workbench, just double-click on the icon AMI-CPC
    to start the emulator.  The @{b}"tooltypes"@{ub} available are:

    - TYPE    : allows to inform the type of the CPC, accepted
                values are:  Amstrad, Schneider...
    - DISC    : allows to give a name to the diskette file that
                AMI-CPC will read by defect. The name can
                include a complete path.  If this tooltype
                is not positioned, AMI-CPC will try to
                open by defect the file "DISC.DSK".
    - SOUND   : if SOUND=ON or SOUND=1, sounds will be
                activated, otherwise, they will be deactivated
    - LROM    : the name (can include a complete path) of the file
                containing the lower rom of a CPC.
                @{b}To have an English keyboard, uses LROM=Roms/lrom_en.@{ub}
    - UROM    : the name (can include a complete path) of the file
                containing the upper rom of a CPC.
    - ROM7    :  the name (can include a complete path) of the file
                containing the AMSDOS rom of a CPC.
    - INT     : indicate the frequency of interrupts :
                if INT=1, interrupts are set to 300 Hz,
                if INT=2, interrupts are set to 150 Hz,
                if INT=3, interrupts are set to  75 Hz,
                if INT=4, interrupts are set to  37 Hz,
    - SMODE   : indicate the ID in hexadecimal format of the default
                screenmode of AMI-CPC.
                Ex : SMODE=0x29000 for PAL: High res. (640x256)
@endnode


##
## 3 Execution
##
@node Execution "Running"

    After starting, you are in front of a CPC.
    AMI-CPC opens its own screen.

  @{b}Using the keyboard@{ub}
    The COPY key of the CPC is "emulate" by the "LEFT-ALT" key, all the
    other keys of the CPC are found on the keyboard of an AMIGA.
    Some keys differ a bit by their sites:

    - the '$' of the CPC is obtained by the AMIGA key:  '\', 
    - the '<' of the CPC is obtained by the AMIGA key:  '*', 
    - the '*' of the CPC is obtained by the AMIGA key:  '$', 
    - the '>' of the CPC is obtained by the AMIGA key:  'Ł', 
    - the '#' of the CPC is obtained by the AMIGA key:  'µ', 
    - the '[' of the CPC is obtained by the AMIGA key:  '°'.

    These keys are only valid for a French keyboard.

    Keys F1, F2, F3, F4 allow to change the frequencies of
    interruptions of the Z80.

    - The F1 key allows switch to the frequency of 300 Hz (as a true CPC)
    - the F2 key allows switch to the frequency of 150 Hz,
    - the F3 key allows switch to the frequency of 75 Hz,
    - the F4 key allows switch to the frequency of 37 Hz.

    By defect, the frequency of interruptions is fixed to 150 Hz.

    On an AMIGA not accelerated (A1200 of basis, for example), I strongly
    dissuade to switch the frequency of interruptions to 300 Hz: indeed,
    with the slowness of instruction emulation, the routine of
    interruptions could have not ended when a new interruption comes, what
    will entail a plantage. (Crushing of the memory with values of return on
    the stack...)
    In fact, the more the frequency is low, the more the emulation will seem
    to be fast, but this will be to the detriment of interruption routines:
    scanning keyboard keys, blinking inks...

    Others keys serve to the functioning of AMI-CPC:

    - F5 : Enter the "DEBUG" mode
           This mode allows to execute instruction Z80 step by step.  
           By pressing F5, a window appears down the screen, with
           information concerning registers of the Z80.  A button 
           right top of this window allows go to the next
           instruction, the closing down of the window (by the
           "close-gadget") returns in the normal mode of emulation.

    - F6 : Displays a requester with informations on AMI-CPC

    - F7 : Allows to "swap floppy disc", by changing the name of the
           file used to emulate a CPC diskette.

    - F8 : Allows to make a "HARD" reset of the CPC, as if you switched-off
           then switched-on a real CPC. (In case of plantage...)

    - F9 : Shows some interesting vectors of AMI-CPC...

    - F10 : Exits the program...

@endnode


##
## 4 what does not function
##
@node DontWork "what does not work..." 

  @{b}Z80 Instructions@{ub}
    Some instructions and fonctionalities of the Z80 are not coded, as:
    - The evolution of the R register is summary: added 1 to each
      instructions...

    - Instructions IM 0, IM 1, IM 2 have no effect (the Z80 is always in
      Interrupt Mode 1).

    - Instructions INI, INIR, IND, INDR, OTIR, OTDR are not coded
      (generate an error message at the end of the emulator if they have
      been executed... (See @{"Last minutes" link LastNote})) 

  @{b}Functionalities of the CPC :@{ub}
    - Only registers 1, 6, 12 and 13 of the CRTC are emulated.

    - The PSG can only generate square signals (no noise, neither
      envelopes...)

    - The printer port is not emulated.

    - µPD 765 is emulated to the minimum to allow read/write under AMSDOS...

    - Surely others things that I have forgotten...

@endnode


##
## 5 what functions
##
@node Work "What functions that work (it seems me) correctly"

  @{b}Functionalities of the CPC@{ub}

    - (Almost!) all instructions documented of the Z80, and the most of not
      documented instructions (SLL r, LD IXH, nn, LD IXL, nn, LD r, Ixh...),

    - PPI 8255, the keyboard, the first joystick with two buttons,
    
    - a part of the PSG AY3-8912 (square signals), white noises,

    - a part of CRTC 6845 (registers 1, 12 and 13),

    - a part of the floppy controller (standard read/write, impossible to
      format at the moment, write does not affect the image disk-file).

  @{b}Emulation of diskettes@{ub}
    The emulation of diskettes is made by a file, that contains the whole of
    diskette data. At the moment, only "standard" format of the CPC are
    recognized. (I have tested only the format DATA, but I think that format
    VENDOR, CPM and IBM will work.) AMI-CPC Reads the .DSK file format. Theses
    files can be XPK packed.

@endnode


##
## 6 Rest to do
##
@node ToDo "Rest to do"

    Unfortunately, a lot functionalities of the CPC are not emulated yet,
    and I have some ideas to improve AMI-CPC:

    - The emulation of the printer port (that can be usefull)...

    - a best emulation of the CRTC,

    - Some utilities, for example for the extraction/insertion of files in
      diskette files, the "grab" of CPC screens...

    And many other things...

    It also remains me to correct some bugs that I have not found yet, but
    that prevents some CPC games to work...

@endnode


##
## 7 Last minutes
##
@node LastNote "Last minutes"

    - If the emulator executes a Z80 instruction not coded (OTIR or
      others...), it will signal before exiting the hexadecimal codes of the
      instruction not coded that it has tempted to execute (for example,
      ED B3 for OTIR).
      Therefore, don't panic, but you can inform me these messages, in order
      that I code missing instructions in a future version...

    - When you press the F10 key, AMI-CPC waits that children tasks end, the
      joystick task has a time-out of 1/10e of second, so it is possible that
      AMI-CPC takes slightly more 1/10e of second between you press the
      F10 key, and the moment of it ends really.

    - The screen of AMI-CPC does not possess Drag-bar (in fact, it is not
      visible (SA_SHOWTITLE is positioned to FALSE...)) therefore, to change
      screen, it is necessary to press <LEFT-AMIGA> + 'M'.

@endnode


